'''''Star Wars'' 53''' is the fifty-third issue in [[Star Wars (1977)|Marvel's ''Star Wars'']] series of comics.

==Plot summary==
[[Princess/Legends|Princess]] [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia Organa]] and [[Captain/Legends|Captain]] [[Chedaki]] pilot a [[CR90 corvette/Legends|blockade runner]] to investigate Imperial activity in the [[Shiva system/Legends|Shiva system]], but as the two are entering a shuttle to go down to the planet [[Shiva IV]], the ship is damaged by a [[Space mine/Legends|space mine]]. Chedaki is killed in the explosion and Leia is forced to launch the damaged shuttle in order to protect the ship and the rest of the crew from harm. The shuttle crashes on Shiva IV and Leia is immediately attacked by a savage raiding party. A group of natives led by [[Aron Peacebringer]] and [[Kéral Longknife]] repel the raiders and rescue the princess. Leia returns to the capital [[Illyriaqüm]] with Aron, and tries to warn him of the danger that the Galactic Empire poses, but the warlord is not convinced that such an empire exists. But during a gala of [[Calian]] nobility, Aron and Leia are both secretly captured by Imperial [[Stormtrooper/Legends|stormtroopers]] and brought before [[General/Legends|General]] [[Bentilais san Sk'ar|Sk'ar]] as prisoners.

==Development==
<!-- This text mostly copied from the Aron Peacebringer article -->
This issue and [[Star Wars (1977) 54|the following one]] were based on unused art for the canceled [[Marvel Comics]] series ''John Carter, Warlord of Mars''. ''Star Wars'' series regular [[Carmine Infantino]] had provided some fill-in art for the series based on [[Wikipedia:Edgar Rice Burroughs|Edgar Rice Burroughs's]] space-fantasy warlord [[Wikipedia:John Carter of Mars|John Carter of Mars]] which was left over after the cancellation; not wishing that the art be wasted, approximately a year after the cancellation Marvel tasked [[Chris Claremont]] with writing a new story based on the existing art and [[Walter Simonson]] with adapting Infantino's art as needed to fit the ''Star Wars'' series. John Carter was turned into [[Aron Peacebringer]] of [[Shiva IV]] in the story that filled these two issues.<ref name="Comic Book Legends Revealed #237">{{WebCite|url=http://goodcomics.comicbookresources.com/2009/12/10/comic-book-legends-revealed-237|text="Comic Book Legends Revealed #237"|work=ComicBookResources.com|archivedate=20091214181040}}</ref> In the ''[[Star-Words]]'' letters column, the issues were passed off as simply inspired by the John Carter stories.<ref name="Star Words">''[[Star-Words]]'' in [[Star Wars (1977) 59|''Star Wars'' (1977) 59]]</ref>

==Continuity==
The story introduces [[Bentilais san Sk'ar|Sk'ar]], Aron Peacebringer, [[Ygal Delois]], [[Alisande]] and [[Kéral Longknife]].

Leia refers to the [[Wikipedia:Cherenkov effect|Cherenkov effect]] when she sees the destroyed city of K'avor. This phenomenon is named after the real-world Russian scientist [[Wikipedia:Pavel Alekseyevich Cherenkov|Pavel Alekseyevich Cherenkov]].

The [[2008]] ''[[The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia]]'' confirmed that the [[TIE series/Legends|TIE Series]] craft appearing on the comic's cover is a [[TIE/br boarding shuttle|TIE boarding craft]], not to be confused with a [[TIE/sh VIP shuttle]].

While not named in this story, Sk'ar's race was [[Retroactive continuity|retconned]] to be Kaleesh in later [[Star Wars Legends|Expanded Universe]] material.

